You said: Here's what the sources say about Fixflo's Co-pilot rules, including available options and functionalities: What is Co-pilot? • Co-pilot is your "friendly works automated assistant", designed to automate tasks and save time. It helps automate works, offering 24-hour protection for occupiers and landlords. • It works by creating rules: if X happens, then Y should happen automatically. "X" represents the filters, and "Y" is the action you want to be taken. Accessing and Managing Co-pilot • Co-pilot is located on the left-hand menu sidebar in Fixflo. • If Co-pilot isn't visible, it may be due to user role permissions, which your manager can adjust. • To add a new rule, click "Add a new rule". You can start with a blank rule or use a template. • Name the rule (under 50 characters) and be as specific as possible. • Enable the rule by clicking the "enabled" button. Rules can be disabled and enabled as needed. Filters • Filters specify the conditions that trigger an action. • When an issue is reported, Co-pilot checks if it matches the set filters. The issue must match your filters exactly in order to automate. • Available filters: ◦ Any: Applies the rule to any issue. ◦ Period: Sets a rule for a specific one-off period of time like a bank holiday or specific months. ◦ Fault: Selects specific fault categories or subcategories to automate. You can select a whole category or drill down for a granular selection. ◦ Fault Priority: Selects certain fault priorities to automate, such as emergency issues. Priorities range from 0 (emergency) to 5 (not urgent). ◦ Time: Sets up automation at recurring times (weekends, evenings, specific hours). ◦ Location: Adds postcodes to automate issues in specific locations. ◦ Property: Sets automation for specific properties. ◦ Property Tag: Uses tags to automate properties with specific characteristics. ◦ Landlord: Sets rules for specific landlords. ◦ Raised By: sets rules based on who raised the issue. • To use the Contractor Marketplace, select "covered by Network" as a filter. Actions • Actions determine what happens when the filters are matched. • You can add up to two actions per rule. • Available actions: ◦ Do Nothing: Prevents any automation for certain postcodes, faults, or times. It means "do not allow co-pilot to do anything". ◦ Notify: Notifies a user (agent, occupier, leaseholders or all occupiers) or an email address with a custom message. ◦ Instruct Works: Automates work orders directly to a contractor. The contractor needs to be on Fixflo already. ◦ Request Quote: Sends a request for a quote. You can request quotes from multiple contractors. Important Considerations • Rule Order: Co-pilot processes rules from top to bottom and automates based on the first rule that matches. The order of the rules is very important. • Testing: It is important to test your rules to ensure they are working as expected. • Co-pilot is good for reactive works; it is not recommended for planned maintenance. Planned maintenance has its own feature for automation. Integrating with Help Me Fix • Co-pilot can automatically dispatch issues in an emergency out of hours. • Set up a Co-pilot rule to have all issues that Help Me Fix can assist with be directed to them automatically. • When setting up a Co-pilot rule to use the Contractor Marketplace, you must select "covered by Network" as a filter. • If you are an Aiden client, your "instruct" action should say, "please send Aiden link". Resources • Fixflo Academy: Provides training courses. • Help Site: Offers articles and videos. • Webinars: Provides updates and Q&A sessions. • Support: Contact Fixflo support for assistance. Creating Issue Creation Rules In Co-Pilot Print Modified on: Tue, 18 Feb, 2025 at 11:44 AM Industry type - all Available with - All Co-pilot allows you to create rules that can automate the following actions: requesting quotes, instructing works or notifying an agent or specific email address when an issue is reported. It’s up to you when these rules run - set them according to issue type reported, property postcode or for a specific time period only. As an example: You could set up a rule that automatically instructs works to a specified contractor when an occupier reports that their gas boiler is broken on a Saturday or Sunday out of office hours. If you wish to edit who does and doesn't have the ability to change Co-Pilot rules, you can read this article here. Setting up Rules 1. First of all go to the Co-Pilot main menu: 2. Click on 'Add New Rule' from the top right. Either pick and amend one of our templates, or add an empty rule and customise: 3. Give your rule a name. Make sure it clearly states what the purpose of the rule is, so it is easy to tell from a glance. For example: 4. Now it's time to set up some filters! Simply click on the below option to do this. 5. Choose an option - fault, location, or time. You can set up rules with any combination of these. Just as an example, we're going to make a rule where: - A gas or electric boiler has been reported as not working. AND - The report has come through outside of your opening hours. Select 'Fault' to choose the applicable issues - you can select as many options as you need and the faults are identical to your fault tree to make it even easier to find what you're after! Here, both gas and electric boilers are selected. Press 'Ok' and this will create your first filter. 6. Now lets add the second filter. For this one, we're going to select the 'Time' filter.You can then specify the applicable times - for example every weekday between 6pm and 9am as well as the weekends. To do this you will need to click and drag to select the hours you want.This will show highlighted in blue.Once this is done press 'Ok' to save this filter. 7. Time to set up an Action! Now that we have set up two filters, we can add the action we want to occur when this criteria is met. Click on the below option to get started. 8. Pick an option. From here, you can request quotes, instruct works, or set up a notification. For this example, we've selected 'Instruct works'. You can then: Pick the contractor you want to allocate works to. Set a works authorisation limit for the job type. Add any instructions notes. Press 'OK' to save the filter. 9. Press 'Save' to setup this rule. You will now see any filters and actions you have set up. All you need to do now is 'Enable' the rule whenever you want it to go live. You will know that the rule is enabled when the slide has gone green. Note: Rules are checked top down - only the first rule to match will run, so make sure they're in order! It's also worth mentioning that when setting up your rules, if you choose the 'Notify' option, you'll have the option of attaching a brief message to go along with them if needs be (below). Co-Pilot Examples Print Modified on: Fri, 29 Nov, 2024 at 8:55 AM Industry type - all Available with - Essentials Co-Pilot allows you to create as many custom rules as you need to automate and streamline your repair and maintenance process. Below are some examples where Co-Pilot can be a really useful tool - we hope these are useful! 1. Instruct all non-technical jobs to your contractor automatically. Auto-instruct issues for faults to do with furniture, internal doors, lighting, keys/access issues etc. to a contractor with a works authorisation limit automatically. This is useful if you have a single handy-man who completes all of these jobs, or does so at properties within a certain area! 2. Request quotes automatically for certain issues (particularly useful for specialist contractors). For instance, broken windows: automatically ‘Request Quotes’ from your glazier so that when you first click into the issue you are presented not only with the problem but also the solution in the form of a submitted quote. 3. Notifications: With Co-pilot you can be really specific with what you want to be notified about. If you manage a set of properties within specific postcodes, get notified outside of office hours of any ‘lock’ issues for your patch only. You can set this up by adding an action to notify the agent. This will then send an email straight to the assigned agent's inbox, notifying them that a 'lock' issue has been reported. 4. Notify landlords If you have certain landlords who prefer to be notified of all repairs at their properties, set up a notification rule specific to them! For more information, check out the guide here. 5. Notify all occupiers when a planned maintenance issue is raised. If you have multiple occupiers at a property, you can set up a co-pilot rule to notify all of them, rather than just the 'reporting occupier', when an issue is raised from a service event. 6. Filter by Managed and non-managed. If you have many non-managed properties, you can set up a co-pilot rule to notify a landlord when an issue is reported. You can also use this filter to filter out properties on the co-pilot rule based on whether they are managed or non-managed to ensure that OOH issues are not instructed for non-managed properties. Reasoned for 17 seconds Below is a concise, high-level overview of what Fixflo’s Co-pilot does and how to set it up, based on the information you provided. What Is Co-pilot? Co-pilot is Fixflo’s rules-based automation tool for property repairs and maintenance. It allows you to create “if X then Y” rules (known as “filters” and “actions”) that automatically handle incoming repair issues—whether that’s notifying the right person, instructing works to a contractor, or requesting quotes. It operates around the clock, saving time for property managers, landlords, and occupiers. How Co-pilot Works You create rules in a top-to-bottom list. When a new issue is reported, Co-pilot starts at the top rule and checks whether the issue meets the “filters” (conditions) you have set. If it matches, Co-pilot immediately applies the “actions” (outcomes) you’ve chosen for that rule. If it doesn’t match, Co-pilot moves on to the next rule, and so on. Important: Once an issue matches a rule, no further rules are applied—so rule order matters! Accessing & Managing Co-pilot Location: You’ll find Co-pilot on the left-hand menu in Fixflo. Permissions: If you don’t see Co-pilot, you may need a manager or admin to enable the feature for your user role. Adding or Editing Rules: Click “Add a new rule”. Choose either a blank rule or one of the templates provided by Fixflo. Name your rule (keep it under 50 characters). Enable or disable it as needed. Filters (the “If” Part) Filters specify the conditions an issue must meet before Co-pilot takes an action. You can combine multiple filters in a single rule (e.g., “fault type” and “time” and “location”). Some key filters: Any – Applies the rule to any issue that comes in. Covered by Network – Targets issues that can be sent to a Contractor Marketplace. Period – Automate for a specific date range (e.g., a bank holiday). Fault – Automate based on the fault category or subcategory (e.g., “Boiler not working”). Fault Priority – Focus on emergency vs. non-emergency (priority 0 to 5). Time – Set rules for specific times or days (e.g., after 6 pm on weekdays, weekends, etc.). Location – Filter by postcode or region. Property – Filter by specific properties. Property Tag – Use property “tags” (e.g., “Student Let”) as a condition. Is managed – Filter managed vs. non-managed properties. Landlord – Target issues belonging to a specific landlord. Raised By – Filter by who reported the issue (occupier, agent, landlord, etc.). Reported as emergency – Filter specifically for issues flagged as emergencies. Actions (the “Then” Part) Actions tell Co-pilot what to do once the filters match. You can choose up to two actions per rule: Do Nothing Blocks further automation for those conditions. Example: If you don’t want Co-pilot to auto-instruct certain high-cost repairs. Notify Sends an email to a chosen recipient (agent, landlord, or a custom email). You can add a custom message for context. Instruct Works Automatically creates a work order to a selected contractor. Set an authorization limit and provide instructions (e.g., “Please fix the boiler ASAP”). Request Quote Sends a quote request to one or multiple contractors. Set a time limit (e.g., 7 days) and any instructions. Rule Order & Best Practices Top to Bottom: Co-pilot reads rules from the first at the top to the last at the bottom. Single Match: Once an issue matches a rule, no further rules apply. Naming: Use clear, descriptive names (e.g., “Instruct Plumber – Boiler Faults Weekend”). Testing: Before fully enabling rules, test them with a sample issue to ensure the correct action triggers. Disable/Enable: You can turn rules on or off any time—especially useful for short-term rules (e.g., holiday coverage). Example Use Cases Instruct All Non-Technical Jobs Filter: Fault categories like furniture, lighting, keys/access. Action: Instruct works to a specific “handyman” contractor. Automatically Request Quotes Filter: Issues like “broken windows,” “roof repair,” or other specialized jobs. Action: Request quotes from your go-to specialists. Notify Specific Team Members Filter: Certain postcodes or property tags. Action: Notify the assigned agent outside office hours (include a custom message). Notify Landlords Filter: Landlord name + property. Action: Notify the landlord whenever an issue is raised. Out-of-Hours Emergencies Filter: Time (evenings/weekends) + Priority (emergency) + Fault type (e.g., “gas leak”). Action: Instruct works to an out-of-hours contractor or an integration like Help Me Fix. Managed vs. Non-Managed Properties Filter: “Is managed” vs. “Is not managed.” Action: For managed, instruct automatically; for non-managed, simply notify the landlord. Integrations (e.g., Help Me Fix, Contractor Marketplace) Covered by Network: If you want to use the Contractor Marketplace (where contractors can pick up jobs), you must select “Covered by Network” as a filter. Help Me Fix: If you have a subscription or integration, Co-pilot can automatically route certain emergencies or video triage issues to Help Me Fix. Aiden: Some clients have “Aiden” as a separate integration, so your “instruct” action might say “Please send Aiden link.” Key Takeaways Co-pilot is designed to save time by automating repetitive tasks. Filters let you specify when and why a rule should run. Actions define what happens next—notify, instruct, or request quotes. Rule order is crucial: the first matching rule wins. Test your rules thoroughly to avoid unintended automation. Further Resources Fixflo Academy: Online training courses for deeper dives. Help Site & Webinars: Articles, videos, and Q&A sessions. Support: Reach out to Fixflo’s support team if you need assistance with advanced configurations or troubleshooting. In essence, Co-pilot is a flexible “if-this-then-that” engine for property maintenance workflows. By carefully setting up filters and actions—and keeping an eye on rule order—you can automate a large portion of your day-to-day maintenance tasks. If there’s anything more specific you’d like to know—like how to create an issue, how to manage user roles, or how to set up Co-pilot rules—just let me know! 1. Dashboard & Tools Setup: Where you configure global settings, user roles/permissions, and general system preferences. Settings: Usually deeper system-wide or account-specific options (like branding, contact details, etc.). Billing details: Payment method, invoices, subscription plans, or credits (if applicable). Content edit: Where you can tweak textual content, email templates, or instructions that appear to users. Design: Theming, logos, or colors for your portal. Fault tree edit: The area to customize your “fault type” or “issue type” tree (all those categories/subcategories). Document library: A repository for shared documents, certificates, manuals, etc. Templates: Saved email templates, contractor instruction templates, or similar. Imports: Bulk-import data like properties, people, or historical issues. Tags: Manage property tags or occupant tags to categorize them. Agency cost codes: If you have cost codes or ledger codes for financial tracking, you manage them here. Manage dashboards / Manage saved searches: Create and edit custom dashboards or saved searches for quick access. Integrations: Connect with third-party tools (e.g., Help Me Fix, Contractor Marketplace, or property management systems). Promote: Typically marketing or promotional tools (depending on your package). Co-pilot: Rules-based automation engine for triaging and instructing issues. Search for issues, places or people…: A global search bar to quickly find issues, properties, or user profiles. My private dashboard: A personalized view of issues or tasks; you can edit/copy/delete or add panels for custom info. 2. People & Users People: Occupiers: Tenants/residents with reported or potential issues. Contractors: Trades or service providers. Landlords: Owners or clients who can be notified or updated. External users: Possibly third-party stakeholders (e.g., building managers, freeholders). Agents: Internal staff or property managers. Teams: Groups of agents or offices (e.g., “Maintenance Team”). User roles: Where you define permission levels. Contractor certification: Track certifications or qualifications for your contractors. Properties: List of all properties, with details like addresses, tags, landlord, or occupant info. Calendar: A unified view of scheduled events, planned works, or deadlines. Reports: Generate system or property/issue-based reports (e.g., monthly maintenance summary). 3. Property Search Quick searching for a specific property address. Options to sort or filter results. 4. Planned Maintenance Compliance matrix: Overview of compliance tasks (e.g., gas safety, EICRs) across properties. Service agreements, service events, service programmes: Tools to schedule recurring or planned works. Event templates: Pre-defined maintenance events (e.g., annual boiler checks). Calendar, Reports: Focused on planned maintenance items. The same “Setup, Integrations, Promote, Co-pilot, Search…” appear as top-level tools. 5. Issues Issue search: Find and filter all reported issues. Issue assignment: A quick way to bulk-assign or reassign issues to agents or contractors. Comments, Projects: Collaborate on issues or group multiple related issues into a “project.” Planned maintenance, People, Properties, Calendar, Reports: The same sub-sections but specifically for reactive repairs or open issues. 6. Create Issue Enter as you go: Manually step through the fault tree on behalf of an occupier. Without a reporting occupier: Log an issue even if you don’t have occupant details. Create on behalf of: If someone phones in, you can log it under their name. Send issue creation link: Let the occupier fill in the details themselves. From another issue: Duplicate or clone an existing issue. Batch create issues: If multiple identical issues need logging (e.g., across multiple flats). 7. Contractor Marketplace Sign up or manage membership in the marketplace, if you want to use validated contractors from the Fixflo network. Director’s details, Bank accounts, Network invoices/payments, etc.: Payment and legal details for the marketplace. Settings: Adjust how you use the marketplace (e.g., auto-instruct or require quotes). Anything Else? If you’re curious about how to do a specific task—like: Setting up Co-pilot rules for certain fault types. Enabling or disabling user roles or permissions. Below is a comprehensive, "no fluff" summary of all key points, rules, filter/action structures, and workflow diagrams from the conversation. It’s meant as a clear, consolidated reference—without repeated explanations or filler.

1. Co-pilot Basic Structure

  • Co-pilot uses “if X (filters) then Y (actions)” rules.

  • A rule has:

    • Filters (e.g., fault type, time of day, landlord, location, etc.).
    • Actions (e.g., notify, instruct works, request quotes).

  • Rule Order: Co-pilot checks from top to bottom. Once an issue matches a rule, it stops checking further rules.

  • Available Filters can be combined:

    • Any (all issues)
    • Fault (choose categories/subcategories)
    • Fault Priority (e.g., 0 = emergency, 5 = not urgent)
    • Time (weekends/evenings/out-of-hours)
    • Location (e.g., postcodes)
    • Property (individual or tagged properties)
    • Landlord (specific landlords)
    • Raised By (occupier, agent, landlord, etc.)
    • Covered by Network (if using a contractor marketplace / network)
    • Period (one-off dates or monthly periods)

  • Available Actions (up to two per rule):

    • Notify (sends a message/email to someone)
    • Instruct Works (assigns a work order directly)
    • Request Quote (asks one or more contractors for quotes)
    • Do Nothing (blocks automation for certain conditions)
    • Send Issue to Integration (e.g., Help Me Fix, Aiden)

  2. Instruct plumber

    • Action: instruct (plumber’s Fixflo contractor record)

  3. Boiler not working

    • Filter: fault type = "Boiler not working"
    • Action: instruct (specific plumber)

  4. Water leak within property

6. “No Response” Escalation

Key Point: Co-pilot alone does not natively time-check for “no response after X hours.” Workarounds include:

  2. Two-Rule:
    • Rule A: “Out-of-hours → manager.”
    • Rule B: Another time-based or status-based approach (e.g., next day 8 a.m. if still “New,” instruct Novex).
  3. API / Webhooks: A custom integration could track timestamps and auto-escalate after 1 hour of no update.

2. Co-pilot: Filters and Actions Overview

  • Filters:

    1. Fault (pick from the massive fault tree above)
    2. Fault Priority (0 = emergency, up to 5 = not urgent)
    3. Time (e.g. out-of-hours)
    4. Location (e.g. postcodes, property tags)
    5. Property (specific named property)
    6. Landlord (specific or any)
    7. Raised By (tenant/occupier, agent, landlord, etc.)
    8. Covered by Network (for contractor marketplace)
    9. Period (bank holidays, monthly windows)
    10. Any (a catch-all)

  • Actions:

    1. Notify (send a notification/email to user or team)
    2. Instruct Works (assign an issue to a contractor directly)
    3. Request Quote (ask multiple contractors for quotes)
    4. Do Nothing (stop other automation)
    5. Send Issue to Integration (for external systems like Help Me Fix or Aiden)

  • Rule Priority/Order: top to bottom; first match stops further checks.

3. Key Example Rules (Short “If → Then” Format)

Below is a short list of commonly used rules. Each example starts with:

less
FOR new issues
IF filters: [...]
THEN actions: [...]

  1. Out-of-Hours Notification

    • IF time = out-of-hours
    • THEN notify (someone or building manager)

  2. Emergency Escalation

    • IF fault priority = 0 (emergency)
    • THEN instruct works (emergency contractor, e.g., Novex) + notify manager

  3. Instruct Plumber (e.g., for “Boiler not working”)

    • IF fault = “Boiler not working”
    • THEN instruct plumber

  4. Water Leak

    • IF fault = “Water leak within property”
    • THEN instruct contractor who handles leaks

  5. Notify Landlord

    • IF landlord + any
    • THEN notify landlord

  6. Help Me Fix (Essentials)

    • IF fault type + “covered by network” + ratecard
    • THEN instruct Help Me Fix + notify staff

  7. Aiden Triage

    • IF (raised by occupant) + (network + ratecard)
    • THEN instruct “please send Aiden link” + notify manager

  8. Fallback

    • IF any (i.e. not matched by prior rules)
    • THEN notify manager for manual review

4. How to Create / Edit Co-pilot Rules

  1. Go to Co-pilot in Fixflo’s left menu.
  2. Click “Add a new rule” (or “Add an empty rule”).
  3. Give the rule a Name (under 50 characters).
  4. Choose your Filters (e.g., time, fault, landlord).
  5. Add Actions (notify, instruct, etc.). You can have up to two actions.
  6. Enable the rule; place it in the correct order (top to bottom).
  7. Test the rule with a sample scenario.

5. Aiden and Help Me Fix Integration

A. Basic Flow

  1. Co-pilot → If the issue matches filters for Aiden, set the action to “please send Aiden link.”
  2. Tenant sees a link or text to chat with Aiden’s AI.
  3. Aiden’s chatbot collects details, can escalate to video triage if needed.
  4. All info returns to Fixflo as a PDF job report or additional notes.
  5. If urgent, Co-pilot can do a second rule to instruct an out-of-hours contractor.

B. Key Phrases

  • When instructing for Aiden, use “please send Aiden link” so Fixflo knows to route it to AI triage.
  • For Help Me Fix you can use “Instruct Help Me Fix,” “Send Issue to Integration,” or “notify + instruct.”

C. Typical Aiden Rule Example

bash
FOR new issues
IF filters: (fault type = plumbing/gas) + (raised by occupant) + (network) + (ratecard)
THEN actions:
   1) notify (Building Manager)
   2) instruct "please send Aiden link"

6. Handling “No Response” / Escalation

No Native Timer in Co-pilot

  • Co-pilot does not have a built-in “wait X hours” feature.
  • Common workarounds:
    1. Manual check next morning for unresponded issues.
    2. Status or Tag approach + second rule.
    3. External integration (API or Webhook) to track time since assignment and auto-escalate.

Example 2-Rule Setup (Hypothetical)

  1. Out-of-Hours → Manager
    • Filters: time = out-of-hours
    • Action: notify manager.
    • (In the message: “Respond within 1 hour or it may escalate.”)
  2. Escalation (Time-based or next day)
    • Filters: if the issue is still “new” or has not changed status
    • Action: instruct Novex or out-of-hours contractor

(However, truly automating “1 hour exactly” needs either a manual check or a custom-coded solution using webhooks.)

8. Webhook & Make.com Integration

A. Webhooks in Fixflo

  • Setup → Webhooks → “Add webhook.”
  • Payload URL: e.g., your Make.com webhook link (like https://hook.eu2.make.com/xxx).
  • HTTP Method: POST.
  • Secret: an optional key for validation (at least 16 chars).
  • Remove Body?: No (so JSON data is sent).
  • Trigger for: “Issue add,” “Issue state change,” “Issue closed,” etc.

B. Make.com (Integromat) Steps

  1. Create a new Scenario in Make.com.
  2. Add a Webhooks module → “Custom webhook.”
  3. Copy the generated URL.
  4. Paste it into Fixflo’s Payload URL.
  5. (Optional) handle the secret in Make.com if you want validation.
  6. Run or activate scenario, then cause an event in Fixflo (e.g., new issue).
  7. Make.com receives the data → you can forward it to WordPress, send an email, store it in Google Sheets, etc.

C. Potential Use Cases

  • Automatic data push to external systems.
  • Setting up a “no-response” timer by storing timestamps in a Make.com workflow.
  • Creating or updating WordPress posts with new issues.

9. End-to-End Workflow Example

Below is a sample scenario describing how everything could fit together:

  1. Tenant reports a “Boiler not working” at 10 p.m. (out-of-hours).
  2. Co-pilot reads top-to-bottom:
    • Emergency rule? If “boiler not working” is flagged as high priority, maybe it instructs out-of-hours (Novex) right away.
    • If it’s not flagged emergency, next rule might be “Out-of-Hours → building manager.”
  3. The manager is notified. Meanwhile, if you also use Aiden for boiler issues:
    • The rule says “please send Aiden link.”
    • The occupant can chat with Aiden, get immediate triage, and a PDF is posted back into Fixflo.
  4. If no manager response by morning (manual check or second rule triggers), automatically instruct Novex or escalate.
  5. Landlord gets notified if you have a rule: “If landlord + any, then notify landlord.”
  6. Webhook fires to Make.com → data is stored in a spreadsheet or posted to your WordPress site for logging.

Below is a further-expanded reference that continues the consolidated overview, adding more detail about people/user management, advanced menu options, and other system elements discussed in the conversation. This builds on the previous “master reference,” so you have a single comprehensive guide.

1. People & User Management

In Fixflo, “People” encompasses occupiers, contractors, landlords, external users, agents, teams, user roles, and contractor certification. Each role interacts differently with issues, Co-pilot rules, and the system’s features.

  1. Occupiers (Tenants/Residents)

    • Typically, the “raised by” filter in Co-pilot will identify them.
    • They can report issues via the portal; those issues then trigger Co-pilot rules.
    • They can receive notifications, updates, or be given direct links (e.g., to Aiden’s chatbot).

  2. Contractors

    • Instruct Works or Request Quote actions in Co-pilot typically direct tasks to them.
    • They can be internal (like an in-house building manager) or external (like “Caberbuild” or “Novex”).
    • Each contractor can have coverage areas, certifications, and login access to view/accept or quote on jobs.

  3. Landlords

    • Co-pilot can have a “Notify Landlord” rule (filter: landlord + any).
    • Landlords can log in to view issues on their properties, if permissions allow.
    • Some prefer auto-approval of low-cost works; others want a quote first—Co-pilot can reflect these preferences (e.g., “notify landlord, request quote” if property = X).

  4. External Users

    • People who are neither your direct staff nor standard tenants/landlords—e.g., freeholders, building managers not fully in your system, or third-party block managers.
    • If they have partial system access, Co-pilot can still notify them or instruct them, provided they’re set up in the “Contractors” or “People” list with the right role.

  5. Agents

    • Internal staff or property managers with various responsibilities.
    • Each agent can have a specific role or belongs to a Team. Co-pilot can “Notify agent” or “Notify team.”

  6. Teams

    • Group of agents (e.g., “Maintenance Team,” “Lettings Team”).
    • If Co-pilot rule says “notify team,” all members get an email or system alert.

  7. User Roles

    • Govern what each user can see or do in Fixflo (e.g., can they edit Co-pilot? Manage contractors? View certain dashboards?).
    • If Co-pilot is missing from someone’s sidebar, it might be a role permission issue.

  8. Contractor Certification

    • A Fixflo feature to record compliance or certification details for a contractor (e.g., Gas Safe, NICEIC).
    • Not directly part of Co-pilot logic, but you can prefer to instruct contractors who have a valid certification for certain fault types.

2. Advanced Menu & Setup Options

The conversation references the left-hand sidebar or top-level navigation items that let you configure or manage Fixflo. Below is a succinct breakdown:

  1. Dashboard & Tools

    • Setup: Global system settings (branding, user roles, email templates).

  • Filters:

    • Instruct Works: You pick from contractors in your “People → Contractors” list.
    • Request Quote: Also references your contractors.

4. Extra Points: Post-Issue Creation vs. Pre-Issue Creation

Sometimes Fixflo can apply rules before an issue is fully created (pre-issue creation) or after it’s created (post-issue creation). This depends on your setup and subscription. For instance:

  • Pre-Issue Creation: If you want the occupant to see certain disclaimers or be redirected to Aiden right away (before logging the final issue).
  • Post-Issue Creation: Standard approach—once the occupant clicks “submit,” then Co-pilot triggers for “new issues” and does the usual logic (notify, instruct, etc.).

When you see options like:

  • “Post issue creation”
  • “Pre issue creation”
  • “Issue creation” They each define at which point in the workflow your rule is applied.

5. Granular Examples Linking People & Fault Types

To illustrate how you might combine the “people” side (building manager, landlord, etc.) with the “fault tree” or location-based contractors:

  1. Rule: “Bathroom Faults at Boden – Instruct Building Manager”

    java
    FOR new issues
IF filters: 
    property = Boden
    fault = Bathroom and Toilet
THEN actions: 
    instruct Building Manager

  2. Rule: “Emergency Gas Leak – Out-of-Hours to Novex”

    java
    FOR new issues
IF filters:
    fault type = "Smell Gas?" 
    priority = 0 (emergency)
    time = out-of-hours
THEN actions:
    instruct Novex (emergency contractor)
    notify (team "EmergencyOps")

  3. Rule: “Landlord Who Must Always Approve”

    vbnet
    FOR new issues
IF filters:
    landlord = "Mr. Jones"
THEN actions:
    notify (Mr. Jones) 
    do nothing (so no auto-instruct happens)

    (He must manually approve or comment; you effectively block further automation by “do nothing.”)

7. Summarized Best Practices

  1. Organize People Properly:

    • Keep your occupant, landlord, contractor data up to date.
    • Use teams for easier notification if multiple staff handle the same tasks.

  2. Use Landlord Notification Rules:

    • “If landlord is set to always be notified → action: notify.”
    • This ensures direct transparency.

  3. Use Building Manager or “Handyman”:

    • For each building or area, create location-based rules so you instruct the right person automatically.

  4. Try a Fallback:

    • Always have a bottom rule: “IF any (no prior rule matched) → Notify manager/team for manual review.”

  5. No Response Escalation:

    • Co-pilot cannot track “time since assigned.” Workarounds: manual checks, daily searches, or custom API/webhook solutions.

  6. Aiden:

    • Combine with a “notify building manager” so that internal staff see the results.

  7. Testing:

    • For each rule, use the “Test rule” option or create sample issues to confirm the correct filter→action path.

    if (issue creation time + 60) is less than now, then escalate.

  • if( ... ; formatNumber(1); formatNumber(0)) returns 1 if the condition is true (i.e., more than 60 minutes have passed) or 0 otherwise.

For module 4 imagine for a second that this is a smart move.. imagine scenarios in Make.com can run for a maximum of 45 minutes.. and this is a clever way to get around that by delaying a restart of the scenario by crashing it.. does that give you a different perspective?

It’s certainly a creative workaround to the 45‑minute limit—essentially forcing the scenario to “fail” so that Make.com retries it after your specified interval. From a purely technical perspective, it can achieve a longer effective “wait” than 45 minutes in one run. However, there are important caveats to keep in mind:

  1. Reliance on “Failure” Mechanics

    • The Flow Control module’s retry mechanism is intended for genuine errors (e.g., if an API call fails).
    • You’re deliberately crashing the scenario so that Make.com interprets it as a failure and re‑executes it.
    • This can be brittle: if anything else goes wrong, or if the data structure changes, you could lose the execution context.

  2. Need for “Storing Incomplete Executions”

    • Make.com only re‑attempts a scenario if it can store the incomplete execution.
    • If that feature isn’t enabled—or if the scenario fails in a way that doesn’t allow re‑storage—you might lose the entire run.

  3. Data Consistency

    • Each retry starts a fresh run, so you have to ensure your variables or partial data (like “exe start”) are still accessible or re‑fetchable.
    • If the scenario is relying on data from the first run, you must store that data somewhere (e.g., Data Store, Google Sheets, or a custom variable in Make.com that persists across runs).

  4. Operation Usage & Complexity

    • Each “fail” and “retry” consumes scenario operations.
    • Debugging can be trickier since each run is technically failing.

  5. Officially Recommended Approach

    • Typically, Make.com recommends scheduled or iterative checks for longer delays. For instance:
      1. Store the issue details (including the creation timestamp) in a Data Store module.
      2. Schedule the scenario to run every X minutes (e.g., every 15).
      3. Compare the current time to the stored timestamp to see if 60+ minutes have elapsed.
      4. If so, escalate.
    • This method avoids artificially crashing the scenario and ensures data is safely stored between runs.

Bottom Line

Yes, using Flow Control to crash and retry can, in theory, bypass the 45‑minute single-run limit and simulate a longer “wait.” It’s clever but also fragile—you’re relying on an error mechanism to handle normal logic, which can make maintenance, debugging, and data integrity more challenging. If you’re comfortable with those trade‑offs, it might work. However, for a stable production setup, a scheduled approach (checking older issues every so often) is typically more robust.

1) Variable Name Mismatch (Trailing Space)

From your logs, your variable name is actually "exe start " (with a trailing space). Meanwhile, in your expression you might be referencing it as exe start (without the space) or vice versa. Make.com treats trailing spaces as part of the variable name, so it will fail to find the correct variable and produce an error.

How to Fix It

  1. Remove the trailing space in the variable name. For example, rename the variable to exactly exe start (no space at the end).
  2. Update your expression so it matches exactly. For example:
    js
    addMinutes(`exe start`, 60)
    (no extra space after “exe start”).

If you keep the trailing space, then your expression must use it too—e.g., addMinutes(`exe start `, 60)—but it’s usually simpler to remove the trailing space altogether.

2) Date Parsing Format

Even if your variable name is correct, Make.com sometimes has trouble parsing a timestamp like 2025-03-04T16:42:27 without specifying a format. By default, it should handle standard ISO 8601 strings, but if it fails, you can be explicit.

How to Fix It
Wrap the date in parseDate() with the correct format. For example:

js
parseDate(`exe start`, "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss")

Then pass that into addMinutes(). A complete example expression might look like:

js
{{ if(
    formatDate(
      addMinutes(
        parseDate(`exe start`, "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss"),
        60
      ),
      "x"
    ) > formatDate(now; "x");
    error("Wait");
    formatNumber(0)
) }}

Here’s what’s happening:

  1. parseDate(exe start, "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss")
    • Converts the text 2025-03-04T16:42:27 into a proper date object.
  2. addMinutes(..., 60)
    • Adds 60 minutes to that date/time.
  3. formatDate(..., "x")
    • Converts the resulting date to a numeric timestamp for comparison.
  4. if(... > formatDate(now; "x"); error("Wait"); formatNumber(0))
    • If the future time is still greater than now, throw an error (deliberate crash). Otherwise, return 0 so the scenario continues.

An alternative, proven solution is to use a Data Store (or another persistent storage module) in combination with a scheduled scenario. Instead of trying to “sleep” in a single long-run scenario (which can be problematic due to the 45‑minute limit), you can do the following:

Overview of the Approach

  1. Capture and Store the Issue Data with Timestamp:
    When an issue is raised, use your webhook (or a Set Variables module) to capture the issue data—including a parsed timestamp (the issue’s creation time). Then, write this data into a Data Store (or similar persistent storage). This gives you a record that won’t be lost when the scenario ends.

  2. Scheduled Scenario for Checking Unacknowledged Issues:
    Create a separate scheduled scenario that runs every few minutes (e.g., every 5 or 15 minutes). In that scenario, retrieve all unacknowledged issues from the Data Store.

  3. Compare Timestamps:
    For each issue, compare the stored timestamp with the current time. If 60 minutes (or your threshold) have passed without the building manager marking it as “acknowledged” or “in progress,” then trigger your escalation actions (for example, instructing Help Me Fix, notifying your team, etc.).

  4. Update or Remove the Issue from the Data Store:
    Once an issue is escalated (or if it’s later acknowledged), update or remove it from the Data Store so that it’s not processed again.

Benefits of This Approach

  • Persistence:
    Using a Data Store means the issue data is stored outside the scenario’s runtime. You’re not limited by the 45‑minute run time of a single scenario.

  • Flexibility:
    The scheduled scenario can be set to run as frequently as needed (every 5, 10, or 15 minutes) so that you can catch delays without forcing the scenario to error.

  • Clarity and Maintenance:
    Separating the “store and wait” part from the “check and escalate” part tends to be easier to manage and debug.

How to Implement It

  1. In Your Initial Scenario (Issue Capture):

    • Use your webhook and Set Variables module to parse and capture the issue creation timestamp.
    • Use a Data Store module (or a Google Sheet module, if you prefer) to save the issue ID, creation timestamp, and any other relevant details.
    • Optionally, flag the issue as “awaiting response.”

  2. Create a Scheduled Scenario (Every 5–15 Minutes):

    • Add a trigger module that runs on a schedule.
    • Use a Data Store “Search” or “List” module to retrieve all issues that are still marked as “awaiting response.”
    • For each issue, compare the stored timestamp with the current time using an expression (e.g., using addMinutes() and formatDate() functions or by converting both to Unix timestamps).
    • If the current time exceeds the stored timestamp by 60 minutes (or more), trigger the escalation:
      • For example, use an HTTP module to call your Help Me Fix API, or a Notify module to send an alert.
    • After escalating, update the status in the Data Store (or remove the record) to avoid duplicate processing.

  3. Error Handling and Logging:

    • Log any errors or issues in the scheduled scenario so you can monitor performance.
    • You can also send notifications if an escalation is triggered, so you have an audit trail.

Conclusion

This method avoids relying on error–retry mechanisms within a single scenario run and gives you a robust, maintainable way to ensure that if the building manager hasn’t responded within the set time, your system automatically escalates the issue.
